    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_644847212" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/644847212" />
    <a title="Supratim" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/21432277-supratim"><img alt="Supratim" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1560446219p2/21432277.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/644847212?book_show_action=true">Dec 05, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Supratim" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Supratim" href="/user/show/21432277-supratim">Supratim</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Mass Market Paperback 9780007420278" href="/book/show/11260667-the-phantom-of-the-opera">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/21432277-supratim?shelf=classic">classic</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/21432277-supratim?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer644847212" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3398410296475811199">A long time ago, before I read this book or even heard about it, I had come across references to the eponymous character of the novel in popular culture. I still remember the mystery shows in good old Cartoon Network where there would be a sinister masked character playing the organ. Enough of nostalgia! Now let’s come to the review of this classic gothic tale. <br/><br/>This is a wonderful example of gothic literature. Not that it needs any certificate of merit from a layman like me, but still! The novel</span>
  <span id="freeText3398410296475811199" style="display:none">A long time ago, before I read this book or even heard about it, I had come across references to the eponymous character of the novel in popular culture. I still remember the mystery shows in good old Cartoon Network where there would be a sinister masked character playing the organ. Enough of nostalgia! Now let’s come to the review of this classic gothic tale. <br /><br />This is a wonderful example of gothic literature. Not that it needs any certificate of merit from a layman like me, but still! The novel was written by French author, Gaston Leroux, and published in 1909. The story in brief: the Opera in Paris is “haunted” by a mysterious character – the Phantom of the Opera aka Erik. He is a physically disfigured individual and has a very cunning and manipulative mind. He acts as the guardian angel to the young, Swedish Christine Daaé. Erik’s instructions are responsible for Christine’s success as a singer. Erik is romantically obsessed with his young protégé and would leave no stone unturned to have her. But, Christine falls in love with another man of course. Otherwise, how could there be a great story! I have said enough. No more!<br /><br />This book has every ingredient to be a gothic romance masterpiece – mystery, adventure, interesting characters, drama and even a little bit of humour. I was hooked on to the story from the very beginning and enjoyed the atmosphere of fear and suspense. Some readers might feel sorry for Erik, but I found him to be too ruthless and manipulative for my sympathies. But, to each his own.<br /><br />I came across the comparison of Erik with Quasimodo from The Hunchback of Notre Dame. Both these characters – physically disfigured men would desire beautiful women, and both the stories revolve around unrequited love. I am yet to read Victor Hugo’s classic – so can’t comment about similarities and differences.<br /><br />Readers need to remember that this book was written in 1909. Therefore, be prepared for an old-fashioned writing style and dialogues. If you don’t mind this, then you will surely enjoy the story.<br /><br />Gaston Leroux has also written some detective novels featuring Joseph Rouletabille. I am keen on those as well. I particularly look forward to The Mystery of the Yellow Room which is regarded as one of the best locked room mysteries. Let’s see when I can get my hands on a copy.<br /><br />Stay safe!<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="3398410296475811199" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


